T1  - Time-varying estimates on the openness of the capital account in Korea and Taiwan
AU  - Reisen, Helmut
AU  - Yèches, Hélène
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 41
IS  - 2
SP  - 285
EP  - 305
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/08/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(93)90060-Z
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789390060Z
AB  - How open are the capital accounts in Korea and Taiwan? Has there been a trend towards more financial openness during the 1980s? This paper aims at answering both questions by estimating a model of interest determination first outlined by Edwards and Khan, in an extension suggested by Haque and Montiel. Use is made of time-varying parameter estimation based on the Kalman filter technique, instead of the usual constant parameter estimation. Our findings indicate a low degree of capital mobility for both Korea and Taiwan, and no trend towards more financial openness (except recently in Taiwan's interbank market). The dismantling of capital controls and of internal financial restrictions is thus likely to impose an important loss of monetary autonomy in both countries.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Performance in living standards: An international comparison
AU  - Kakwani, N.
JO  - Journal of Development Economics
VL  - 41
IS  - 2
SP  - 307
EP  - 336
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/08/01/
SN  - 0304-3878
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3878(93)90061-Q
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789390061Q
AB  - Our ultimate objective is to enhance the standard of living of our societies. But the standard of living has different meanings for different people. A thorough investigation of the concept of the standard of living has been made only recently by Sen, who defines it in terms of functioning and capabilities. Functioning is an achievement, whereas capability is the ability to achieve. The main objective of the present paper is to compare achievements (levels) and improvement (changes) in the standard of living across countries. Using an axiomatic approach, an achievement index is derived which accomodates the view that a further increase in the standard of living of a country when it is already at a higher level signifies an achievement greater than that of another with an equal increase but from a lower base. The paper also tests for the statistical relationship between indicators of the countries' standards of living so derived in their capita GDP. The question posed is whether the aggregate income which provides people with the means to achieve a better life, can be used as proxy measure of the standard living and extent to which the country's improvement in the standard of living can be explained by the levels and changes in the per capita income. The analysis presented in the paper is based on the data from 80 developing countries.
ER  - 

