UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/030438789390058U
AB  - In agricultural tenancy arrangements, the tenant is often required to undertake effort aimed at maintaining and improving the productive stocks. This paper investigate the design of contracts which induce optimal investment of such effort. It is found that a long-term contract which interlinks tenancy with a credit agreement is optimal. In equilibrium the tenant obtains credit from the landlord at a rate of interest below the market, and is perpetually indebted to the landlord.
